1. Dispersion relation for R-wave with electrons (e), positrons (p), and ions (i):
$$
n_R^2=1-\frac{\omega_{pe}^2}{\omega(\omega+\Omega_{ce})}
-\frac{\omega_{pp}^2}{\omega(\omega-\Omega_{ce})}
-\frac{\omega_{pi}^2}{\omega(\omega+\Omega_{ci})}.
$$
2. Quasi‚Äêneutrality: $-e n_e+e n_p+e n_i=0\implies n_e=n_p+n_i$. Hence
$$
\omega_{pe}^2-\omega_{pp}^2=\frac{(n_e-n_p)e^2}{m_e\epsilon_0}
=\frac{n_i e^2}{m_e\epsilon_0}
=\omega_{pi}^2\frac{m_i}{m_e}.
$$
3. Under $\omega\ll\Omega_{ce}$, approximate $\omega+\Omega_{ce}\approx\Omega_{ce}$ and $\omega-\Omega_{ce}\approx -\Omega_{ce}$. Under $\omega\ll\Omega_{ci}$, approximate $\omega+\Omega_{ci}\approx\Omega_{ci}$. Then
$$
n_R^2
=1-\frac{\omega_{pe}^2}{\omega\Omega_{ce}}
+\frac{\omega_{pp}^2}{\omega\Omega_{ce}}
-\frac{\omega_{pi}^2}{\omega\Omega_{ci}}
=1-\frac{\omega_{pe}^2-\omega_{pp}^2}{\omega\Omega_{ce}}
-\frac{\omega_{pi}^2}{\omega\Omega_{ci}}.
$$
4. Substitute $\omega_{pe}^2-\omega_{pp}^2=\omega_{pi}^2(m_i/m_e)$ and note $m_i/m_e=\Omega_{ce}/\Omega_{ci}$:
$$
\frac{\omega_{pe}^2-\omega_{pp}^2}{\Omega_{ce}}
=\frac{\omega_{pi}^2\,m_i/m_e}{\Omega_{ce}}
=\frac{\omega_{pi}^2\,\Omega_{ce}/\Omega_{ci}}{\Omega_{ce}}
=\frac{\omega_{pi}^2}{\Omega_{ci}}.
$$
Thus
$$
n_R^2=1-\frac{\omega_{pi}^2}{\omega\Omega_{ci}}
-\frac{\omega_{pi}^2}{\omega\Omega_{ci}}
=1-\frac{2\omega_{pi}^2}{\omega\Omega_{ci}}.
$$
5. Cutoff $\omega=\omega_{cut}$ occurs when $n_R^2=0$:
$$
1-\frac{2\omega_{pi}^2}{\omega_{cut}\,\Omega_{ci}}=0
\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
\omega_{cut}=\frac{2\omega_{pi}^2}{\Omega_{ci}}.
$$
